ty":"full","cve_ids":[],"singular_disclosure_disabled":false,"disclosed_at":"2017-06-02T10:04:08.827Z","bug_reporter_agreed_on_going_public_at":"2017-06-02T10:04:08.762Z","team_member_agreed_on_going_public_at":"2017-06-02T09:54:21.185Z","comments_closed?":false,"facebook_team?":false,"team_private?":false,"vulnerability_information":"##Description\nI saw the fixed issue in the https://hackerone.com/reports/223692 and i think i found another filter bypass. I noticed that we actually can use special keywords like %(branch)s, %(file)s and %(line)s.\nSo XSS can be achieved in this way:\n`%(branch)s:alert(1);//https://`\nif the branch will be named `javascript`, the payload will be executed upon pressing the source code link of the file inside it.\n\n##Steps to reproduce\n1. Create some branch and name it javascript\n2. Put some source files.\n3. Click the link on source file. The `%(branch)s` will be replaced by branch name (`javascript`) and popup will be fired.\n\n##Suggested fix\nI recommend you to additionally sanitize string by disallowing special symbolst before first `:` occurence (if exist)","weakness":{"id":60,"name":"Cross-site Scripting (XSS) - Generic"},"original_report_id":null,"original_report_url":null,"attachments":[{"id":185868,"file_name":"zx.JPG","expiring_url":"https://hackerone-us-west-2-production-attachments.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/000/185/868/d27b10e213a05697043c7a9fb3edb761955d5465/zx.JPG?response-content-disposition=attachment%3B%20filename%3D%22zx.JPG%22%3B%20filename%2A%3DUTF-8%27%27zx.JPG\u0026response-content-type=image%2Fjpeg\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=ASIAQGK6FURQWB754HSG%2F20260429%2Fus-west-2%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20260429T102445Z\u0026X-Amz-Expires=3600\u0026X-Amz-Security-Token=IQoJb3JpZ2luX2VjECoaCXVzLXdlc3QtMiJIMEYCIQCkvKMfp%2BRGEfkHq0HWEFGPIqF6wavPtcKw6MXqoY6aZAIhAN1GgDvvrDbqUDXsnpvSwusA2BCrcpSWyhj0LuMejNEJKrsFCPP%2F%2F%2F%2F%2F%2F%2F%2F%2F%2FwEQAxoMMDEzNjE5Mjc0ODQ5IgxU3f5Zht8Qzx3x